metadata.name: Step by Step #48
metadata.description:
Step by Step explores the feeling of being stuck, confined - walking the path ahead of you often only seeing the immediate next step until exhaustion. We all feel this way from time to time — in our lives, jobs, bodies, situations — yet in our search for something, we shouldn't forget that there can still be beauty along the path.

The project takes some inspiration from Henri Matisse, both in the aesthetics of his later works (i.e. the "Cut Outs") and metaphorically in the sense that he had underwent medical treatment which left him wheelchair- or bed-bound towards the later part of his life, forcing him to give up painting, yet in his exploration of this new creative medium which involved cutting paper and pinning them up, his unorthodox work went on to become the most transformative of his career.

Released as part of the 4th edition of the Cure³ Parkinson's cure fundraiser exhibition organized by Artwise Curators and Bonhams as part of a specially comissioned selection of generative artists minting NFTs, curated by Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick with the support of fx(hash) at Bonhams, London from 13-17th January 2023.

---
33% of primary sales and 3% of secondary sales will be donated on-chain to Cure Parkinson’s
---

Controls:
• 'R' regenerates the piece (e.g. in case the window size changes)

Made in p5js
Created Jan 2023
Artist: Yazid

metadata.name: 7.356 degrees #75
metadata.description:
Start with something simple. Take four identical equilateral triangles and join them to form a pyramid. This is your building block – a regular tetrahedron, the simplest possible three-dimensional figure.

When you connect five such pyramids by attaching their faces, you will be left with a thin empty space between the first and last: a volumetric angle of 7.356 degrees. It’s too small to fit another piece and too big to be lost in numerical imprecision.

It is a surprising imperfection. You would expect a tetrahedron to behave similarly to its two-dimensional ancestor. When you arrange equilateral triangles, one next to the other like tiles, you can cover two-dimensional space without leaving an empty spot. You may go on forever, covering infinite planes and be sure that the six angles that meet at each point will add up to the perfect 360 degrees.

In three dimensions, it is not like this: you cannot use your building block to fully fill a void. It’s as if the mathematical rules –the ones we tend to idealise for elegance, harmony, and infallibility– broke when you raise complexity.

But mathematical beauty does not reside in perfection. It is through these exceptions that complexity emerges. So keep building, face by face, one block at a time, and embrace the surprising, chaotic aesthetics that appears. A different type of harmony – not based on impeccable proportions, but on unpredictability.

---

The colours of the structures are inspired by 16 paintings of Polish artists from the 19th and 20th centuries.

"In a window" by Anna Bilińska-Bohdanowicz
"Portrait of Jadwiga against a Yellow Background" by Józef Mehoffer
"Portrait of Zofia Okuń" by Edward Okuń
"Girl with chrysanthemums" by Olga Boznańska
"Nocturne – Swans in Ogród Saski in Warsaw by Night" by Józef Pankiewicz
"Soil" by Ferdynand Ruszczyc
"Obsession" by Wojciech Weiss
"Self-portrait in armour" by Jacek Malczewski
"Self-portrait" by Artur Grottger
"Portrait of Jadwiga Dembowska" by Leopold Horowitz
"Death of Barbara Radziwiłł" by Józef Simmler
"Before the Sunrise" by Józef Chełmoński
"With brushwood" by Julian Fałat
Study for the painting "In a Bower" by Aleksander Gierymski
"Woman Combing her Hair" by Władysław Ślewiński
"Still life with a heron" by Władysław Czachórski

---

Click on the image for resolution options.

In live mode:

Click PNG to save the rendered image. [Saving higher resolutions may not work in some browsers; in these cases, right-click-save the image]

Click STL or PLY to download the digital model to view on your computer or 3d print at home [experimental - highly complex geometries are difficult to 3d print in practice]. The PLY format stores colours of the model that can be visualised in most 3d modelling programs.

metadata.name: Adjacent #104
metadata.description:
Adjacent is the third in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art. This piece focuses on the study of Diagonal White, a series he developed between 1970 and 1975.

In 1976, Ruth Leavitt published a collection of papers titled "Artist & Computer", which highlighted the 35 prominent generative artists and asked them to discuss their work. They were posed questions like, "Do you feel art work created with a computer has now or will have an impact on art as a whole in the future?". Edward Zajec was a subject of one of those papers and in it detailed the approach to Diagonal White. 

The original program was run on a CDC 6200 computer at The Univeresiry of Trieste. The programming was done in collaboration with Dr. Matjaz Hmeljak, his long-time technical partner. Inspired by his collaborative relationship, Adjacent the output of a partnership between Christine Hall and Chris Maddern.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall and @chrismaddern

metadata.name: (recombination/perspectives)-I: Horizons #20
metadata.description:
🌊 🌞 🌈 🌅


    ( r e c o m b i n a t i o n  /  p e r s p e c t i v e s ) 


                     I :   H o r i z o n s


                            ✨ 🧬 🧡 ⏲







-----
* What/How *

2 560 000 particles are subjected to a succession of 64 energy bursts which scatters the points through space. 
The algorithm then stores 3 configurations of points, forming an entangled coherent system.
After few seconds multiple observation modalities are then selected sequentially to allow for dynamic and contemplative visualization.

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a 2160x2160 PNG bitmap and an infinite randomly deterministic animation.

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 → 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL / GLSL
- Unique generative, random and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Infinite animation
- Animation sequences duration between 6 and 60 seconds.

-----
* Controls *

Keyboard "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

Keyboard "X" : skip current animation sequence / next sequence

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&fastdemo=on"
Forces animation sequences to last 10 seconds instead of random durations.

"&slow=on"
Forces animation sequences to last 1 minute instead of random durations.

"&static=on"
Disables animation automatic start. Press "X" to start animations.


-----
@HAL09999 – January 25th, 2023

metadata.name: Clerestory #11
metadata.description:
Windows welcome daylight, admit fresh air, and offer a view into the outside world. They rarely shatter, always confess the passage of time, and sometimes allow others a chance to look in.

What would the space you're in feel like if it had no windows?

'Clerestory' is an abstract exploration of stained glass windows, drafting shattered sketches for ten potential locations from various perspectives and moments in time. 

Made with WebGL, p5.js, and <3 | CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: In Between #3
metadata.description:
In Between

Genuary is an artificially generated month of time where we build code that makes beautiful things, with 31 prompts to base your code art off. Genuary 2023 took place during the month of January 2023. Afterwards, as it happens, comes Genuary 32nd. This is an imaginary week, during which we develop one of our Genuary pieces into a 32 edition "not very long"-form generative project on fx(hash).

My Genuary 32nd project is based on Genuary 22nd: Shadows, the design of which again was based on the "art deco" pattern from day 20.

The patterns form a grid-like fence structure, dividing the space and creating an infinite cage. Light coming from the outside casts stark shadows on the floor. Several variations on halftoning techniques are used to portray tone, occasionally destroying depth perception into an abstract interplay of form.

The code of this piece has been diminished into a mere 3397 characters.

You can use the URL-parameter &m=2 as a resolution multiplier, to render images larger than your screen.

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma. https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: Algorithm, be my guide #172
metadata.description:
At length, I summoned the courage to approach.

-

I was worn. Months of aimless wandering have culminated in this series; a meditation on my struggles to find a direction in my life and with my art.

At times paralyzed by too many possibilities, and at other times completely void of ideas. I was lost in the depths of my thinking, overwhelmed by indecision and doubt.

Generative works are a form of process art, yet along the way I’d forgotten to “trust the process”. It was time to cede control and let each line of code light the way.

-

This project paints on a 2D canvas, pixel by pixel. I used a custom projection that blends isometric and perspective techniques, to create an uncanny viewpoint between the two. Objects are randomly generated, then an algorithm applies color mixing and position displacement to each pixel as it’s rendered.

By default the canvas has 2k pixels on its longest edge. You can change this in live view by pressing any number from 1-9. For example, pressing ‘4’ would render it with 4k pixels along the longest edge. I recommend ‘4’, but this can take up to a few minutes to render.

Press ‘s’ to save the rendered image.

metadata.name: glory hole$ #439
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

metadata.name: .cloths (Japan color) #54
metadata.description:
For this Token, I was inspired by Japanese culture and incorporated colors traditionally associated with Japan into the palette.

The traditional Japanese colors, regularly tiled, resemble the scales of Nishikigoi or the patterns of a kimono (furisode) patterns.

The shearing deformation of the tile shapes; shear() makes the colors appear abstract.

The palette is selected from one of the following variations.

01. Ninja(忍者)　02. Tsukimi(月見)　03. Fuji & Moon(富士と月)　04. Urushi(漆)　05. Red Fuji(赤富士)　06. Tonosama(殿様)　07. Daimyo(大名)　08. Cherry Blossom(桜)　09. Autumn Leaves(紅葉)　10. Furisode(振り袖)　11. Nishikigoi(錦鯉)　12. Uji Kintoki(宇治金時)　13. Samurai(侍)

I would be happy if you could feel the beauty of Japan, my birthplace, even a little.

metadata.name: Blurevich #45
metadata.description:
"Blurevich"

The painting is characterized by its non-representational style, where the rectangles are not meant to depict recognizable objects or figures. 
Instead, the blurred rectangles serve as visual elements that create a sense of movement and dynamism in the painting. 
The use of blurriness in the rectangles gives the painting a hazy and ethereal quality. 
The colors used in the painting would  be bold and striking, creating a striking contrast between the sharp edges of the rectangles and the soft, blurred edges. 
The overall effect of the painting is one of abstraction and experimentation, express our emotions.

metadata.name: The Visual Code #1
metadata.description:
The Visual Code is a collection of generative art that celebrates the jazzy, dynamic visuals inspired by Wassily Kandinsky, Jackson Pollock, Kazimir Malevich, Joan Miro and The Dave Brubeck Quartet's music.

Each piece uniquely expresses the artist's creativity and technical skill, showcasing the beauty and complexity of computer-generated visuals.

As a codegen artist, I am constantly in awe of the boundless potential of generative art. The ability to create unique, one-of-a-kind pieces using code is truly fascinating to me.

Generative art allows for a level of artistic expression that is simply not possible with traditional mediums. Using algorithms and mathematical principles allows for creating complex, dynamic visuals that are constantly evolving and changing.

What I find particularly interesting about generative art is its focus on the creation process. Rather than simply producing a static, finished product, the artist is more concerned with the journey and the process of creating the art. This allows for experimentation and exploration that is impossible in more traditional forms of art.

In my own work, I strive to push the boundaries of generative art and explore new possibilities. I constantly experiment with different algorithms and techniques to create something new and unique.

I am excited to continue learning and growing as an artist and to see where my passion for generative art will take me.

The collection is a tribute to the art of coding and its endless possibilities for artistic expression. From mesmerizing geometric patterns to pulsating colour fields, each piece in the collection is a testament to the endless potential of code as a medium for artistic creation.

Previous collectors are automatically on the reserve list for this exclusive collection. This is a rare opportunity to own a piece of generative art that captures the imagination and celebrates the beauty of code.

Press [S] to save.

metadata.name: Errance #180
metadata.description:
Errance - an exploration of abstract and digital glitch fusion. The algorithm crafts the concept and structure, while randomness navigates the detailed textures, exploring the interplay between systematic design and the unforeseen aspects of randomness. Errance represents a journey of discovery, one without a defined endpoint, capturing the unexpected and fortuitous outcomes that emerge as algorithms navigate freely, leaving a trail of unique and unpredictable patterns.

Best experienced in live mode at high resolution, the outputs vary significantly due to multiple features, occasionally favouring a slightly asymmetric balance. Under the hood, the algorithm employs a combination of recursive functions, 3D primitives, and multiple textures derived from trigonometric and noise functions using p5.js. Last but not least, during rendering, the outputs are enhanced by one of several versions of a GLSL shader.

In live mode:
-press 1 to save a 2K-resolution PNG copy.
-press 2 for a 4K-resolution PNG copy.
-press 3 to render a version without passepartout.
-press 4 for a 2k-resolution PNG copy without passepartout.
-press 5 for a 4k-resolution PNG copy without passepartout.

metadata.name: MetaSignal: Lexicon #53
metadata.description:
The project is a reinterpretation of my previous "MetaSignal", with a different key.

Two one-dimensional 3-states cellular automata intersect to form a grid with a total of nine states.
A two-dimensional cellular automata extracts details from the grid.

This complex configuration enhances the veil of mystery surrounding how intricate and captivating structures emerge from simple random rulesets.
I invite you to search and reflect about the hidden layers of meaning, hoping you will find yours.

---

16 messages, 3 sampling methods, a small probability of receiving a broken signal.

• Clicking/tapping on the canvas shows a menu to pause, resume, reverse generation direction and download the current 1080x1080 pixels frame.

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | IG: @outertales | September 2023

   Per aspera ad astra.
